WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:12.680
I'm Jim Kloet. I manage a team of data scientists in Chicago, and I am here to talk about garbage

00:00:12.680 --> 00:00:18.240
data. But before I talk about garbage data, I want to lead you off with a quote. A lot

00:00:18.240 --> 00:00:22.440
of you have probably seen this quote before. It's about statistical models. It's from the

00:00:22.440 --> 00:00:27.760
famous statistician George Fox. And he wrote a bunch of times, at least the first part,

00:00:27.760 --> 00:00:33.200
all models are wrong, but some are useful. But then sometimes he'd go on, he'd add things

00:00:33.200 --> 00:00:38.200
like, so the question you need to ask yourself is not, is the model true? Because it never

00:00:38.200 --> 00:00:44.040
is. But is the model good enough for this particular application? And I love this quote.

00:00:44.040 --> 00:00:49.480
It's true. It's not explicitly about garbage data, but it turns out that you can just cross

00:00:49.480 --> 00:00:56.480
out models and replace it with data. And the quote's still true. Because all data are wrong,

00:00:56.480 --> 00:01:00.840
but some are useful. There's no such thing as a perfect data collection tool or data

00:01:00.840 --> 00:01:06.860
retention tool. And so the question that you need to ask yourself isn't, are the data true?

00:01:06.860 --> 00:01:11.879
Because they're not. But are the data good enough for this particular application? And

00:01:11.879 --> 00:01:18.919
so the you in this sentence that I'm thinking of is us, data professionals. And depending

00:01:18.919 --> 00:01:24.000
on where you're at, whether you're in industry or academia, the titles are going to differ.

00:01:24.239 --> 00:01:30.239
It could be a data scientist or engineer or architect or academic researcher. The point

00:01:30.239 --> 00:01:35.720
is though that we data professionals are often the primary deciders of data usefulness in our

00:01:35.720 --> 00:01:41.279
organizations. And a typical workflow, at least for me, kind of looks like this. So we'll have

00:01:41.279 --> 00:01:45.720
some stakeholders that are super enthusiastic. I use a lot of emojis. So if you don't like

00:01:45.720 --> 00:01:52.160
emoji, you should leave. So stakeholders will be really enthusiastic. They'll come to us and ask

00:01:52.160 --> 00:01:57.080
for help. Like they brought us some data and I don't work in agriculture. This is a metaphorical

00:01:57.080 --> 00:02:03.879
haystack. And so then we spring into action and we think, okay, cool. We're on this hypothetical

00:02:03.879 --> 00:02:10.039
continuum of data usefulness. Do we think that these data should fall? And if they're maximally

00:02:10.039 --> 00:02:16.600
useful, the best case scenario is that they are just chock full of insights, which you see,

00:02:16.600 --> 00:02:21.000
the metaphor keeps going. Now we've got needles. Answers to our questions, solutions to our

00:02:21.000 --> 00:02:27.199
problems, whatever the stakeholders are looking for. Because I mean, ultimately, stakeholders

00:02:27.199 --> 00:02:32.639
expect that there's going to be something in data, right? Like that's the promise of big data. And so

00:02:32.639 --> 00:02:38.000
even if we make this assessment that data are minimally useful, the expectation from our

00:02:38.000 --> 00:02:42.800
stakeholders is still like there's non-zero insights in there, right? Like that there's

00:02:42.800 --> 00:02:48.880
at least a needle in the haystack or two needles. And again, people are led to believe that data

00:02:48.880 --> 00:02:55.199
are always going to be the solution here. They're not going to be the problem. But I think Megan's

00:02:55.199 --> 00:03:01.639
talk highlighted, Max Kuhn's keynote this morning also called out data aren't always useful. And in

00:03:01.639 --> 00:03:07.320
a lot of cases, data are just garbage. And garbage data are at all of our organizations, right? I

00:03:07.320 --> 00:03:12.639
think if you've worked with real world data, you definitely have encountered garbage data. And so

00:03:12.639 --> 00:03:17.960
you know then that garbage data is problematic and has costs and can lead to real problems within

00:03:18.000 --> 00:03:22.559
our organization. So my talk here, I want to make sure you all walk away with at least three points.

00:03:22.559 --> 00:03:27.800
First, I want to make sure you can identify garbage data in your organizations. Second, I want to make

00:03:27.800 --> 00:03:33.119
sure that you're aware of and can identify the costs of garbage data. And then finally, I want

00:03:33.119 --> 00:03:38.440
to make sure that you're taking action when you see garbage data. All right, so hitting the first

00:03:38.440 --> 00:03:44.559
point here on identifying garbage data. So like we think an operational definition is a good starting

00:03:44.559 --> 00:03:50.160
point. And garbage data, I think, simply are just data that aren't useful for a particular application.

00:03:50.160 --> 00:03:54.960
So if we have stakeholders coming up to us, then the first question we really need to ask them is,

00:03:54.960 --> 00:03:59.759
are the data that you're giving us that we're working with relevant for the questions that

00:03:59.759 --> 00:04:06.080
you're interested in asking? And so say our stakeholders come up with questions about hot

00:04:06.080 --> 00:04:13.960
dogs. And then they give us data like this. And it's adorable. And it's possibly useful based on

00:04:14.479 --> 00:04:19.440
the simple dogs being in there. Hat tip to Hadley for this joke, by the way, in the feedback. Thank

00:04:19.440 --> 00:04:25.239
you, Hadley. But as we're making our decision about how the data are useful or not, it's quite likely

00:04:25.239 --> 00:04:29.279
that we'll probably say, no, these data aren't relevant to the particular application. They're

00:04:29.279 --> 00:04:34.119
likely not going to be able to answer your questions. But our questions usually don't

00:04:34.119 --> 00:04:38.959
stop there, right? We've identified the garbage data, but garbage data aren't always garbage.

00:04:39.040 --> 00:04:44.440
They could be relevant for a different thing. So the next question we want to ask our stakeholders,

00:04:44.440 --> 00:04:50.519
is there another application where these data could be relevant? And so if your stakeholders

00:04:50.519 --> 00:04:54.119
are anything like mine, they have lots of questions. It's not just that their questions

00:04:54.119 --> 00:04:59.399
are about hot dogs or one thing in particular. Oftentimes the data that they have are probably

00:04:59.399 --> 00:05:04.320
relevant to something else that they're interested in. And so working with them to find out if there's

00:05:04.399 --> 00:05:09.720
another question that the data can be helpful in answering seems like is another reasonable step

00:05:09.720 --> 00:05:15.440
to take. I think that there's one other step to take after this, though. Say you say no,

00:05:15.440 --> 00:05:22.519
and the data are not necessarily useful for this secondary application. I think it's fair to ask,

00:05:22.519 --> 00:05:27.559
are there reasons to expect that these data are total garbage? Because again, we've worked with

00:05:27.559 --> 00:05:32.519
real world data. We know that there are definitely cases where your data are not useful for anything.

00:05:32.519 --> 00:05:39.000
And that often requires us to put on our sleuthing hats, which is usually a part of any data

00:05:39.000 --> 00:05:44.760
professionals arsenal. I'm not going to go into all of the ways that data can be totally garbage,

00:05:44.760 --> 00:05:48.040
but I'm going to walk through at least a few examples because I'm sure that they will resonate

00:05:48.040 --> 00:05:52.359
with some of us. Megan also had a ton of awesome examples in her talk as well, so check out that

00:05:52.359 --> 00:05:58.279
repo. So things can go wrong during data collection. I used to work with handwriting data. Sometimes

00:05:58.399 --> 00:06:03.320
that data is illegible. This is not data from any of my previous studies. This is actually from a

00:06:03.320 --> 00:06:08.000
New York Times article about kids' handwriting. But the point I think is still well taken,

00:06:08.000 --> 00:06:14.480
that sometimes the data is just completely borked from the point of collection. It can also get

00:06:14.480 --> 00:06:20.320
screwed up in retention, right? I've had a weird case where some of my data were corrupted from a

00:06:20.320 --> 00:06:25.000
hard drive failure, but not all of it. And it didn't become clear until I'm doing a little bit

00:06:25.000 --> 00:06:28.760
more digging and reading a whole bunch of logs, which is not my favorite way of spending time.

00:06:28.760 --> 00:06:33.640
And so retention is another opportunity for things to really go wrong and make your data

00:06:33.640 --> 00:06:42.160
totally garbage. Nineties kids, Steve Urkel. So a lot of times the total garbage results from

00:06:42.160 --> 00:06:47.000
someone accidentally borking the data. I have done this more times than I can count. And if

00:06:47.000 --> 00:06:51.559
there's anyone in the room who has not accidentally borked their data to make it useless or very close

00:06:51.559 --> 00:06:56.359
to useless, raise your hand. Well, actually don't raise your hand because it's going to

00:06:56.359 --> 00:07:01.079
happen sooner or later. So just be prepared for that sort of thing. So people make mistakes all

00:07:01.079 --> 00:07:05.839
of the time in data collection and retention. And so that's sometimes how data will become

00:07:05.839 --> 00:07:11.320
totally useless. I think a recent case is where we had a lot of data that were replaced by default

00:07:11.320 --> 00:07:16.679
values. And so when it looked like 99% of our sample were default values, we had to start

00:07:16.679 --> 00:07:22.440
wondering if that was going to be useful for inference. The last case, which I think makes

00:07:22.440 --> 00:07:27.399
a lot of news and headlines is that sometimes people intentionally bork their data. This is

00:07:27.399 --> 00:07:31.239
what I think we used to think cyber criminals looked like. Maybe this is what they actually

00:07:31.239 --> 00:07:38.839
look like. I'm not sure. I don't necessarily think that this is like the most common scenario, right?

00:07:38.839 --> 00:07:45.000
People usually seem to be honest in my experience with their data, unless they're really incentivized

00:07:45.000 --> 00:07:50.760
to have data look a very specific way. So I guess if those cases are arising, which I don't think

00:07:50.760 --> 00:07:55.519
I've ever had in my career, that might be an opportunity where totally garbage data could

00:07:55.519 --> 00:08:01.679
be arising. So in those cases, what do you do? You've identified that the data are totally garbage.

00:08:01.679 --> 00:08:07.079
Those need to be destroyed. I think in most cases. I can point to a number of times when I've worked

00:08:07.079 --> 00:08:11.160
with folks that have tried to make inferences from totally garbage data, and we'll get into

00:08:11.160 --> 00:08:16.799
the consequences of those in a little while. But if you can't put up, or if you can't totally

00:08:16.799 --> 00:08:20.880
destroy the data, put up as much warning tape as you possibly can, because you want to make

00:08:20.880 --> 00:08:27.040
sure that nobody else is trying to accidentally make inferences out of this. So identifying data

00:08:27.040 --> 00:08:31.720
is useful. Identifying garbage data is useful. But I called out that there's a reason to do it,

00:08:31.720 --> 00:08:38.159
and it's because garbage data, oops, excuse me, I had a summary slide. So summing up part one,

00:08:38.200 --> 00:08:43.760
some garbage data are not useful. Some garbage data are useful for other stuff,

00:08:43.760 --> 00:08:50.760
some not useful for anything. So why do we care? Well, it's because garbage data have costs. And

00:08:50.760 --> 00:08:56.799
I think of those costs in a couple different ways. I think first of these unavoidable costs

00:08:56.799 --> 00:09:01.919
that you're going to have anytime you have a data project, right? This is a just example cloud bill,

00:09:01.919 --> 00:09:07.440
because every time you have a data project, you're going to incur costs with data collection,

00:09:07.599 --> 00:09:14.080
data retention, any kind of support around those data. There's always going to be a cost. Your data

00:09:14.080 --> 00:09:19.760
lake, your cloud provider doesn't know, probably doesn't care if your data are garbage. Those costs

00:09:19.760 --> 00:09:25.599
are going to happen whether your data are good or not. You might not be able to avoid some costs,

00:09:25.599 --> 00:09:29.320
but the avoidable costs I think are really the ones you have to be on the lookout for,

00:09:29.320 --> 00:09:36.679
because that can really torpedo your organization. So first, the excessive regular old data costs,

00:09:36.799 --> 00:09:41.320
if you don't catch the fact that you have garbage data, well, you're just going to keep incurring

00:09:41.320 --> 00:09:45.799
bills and bills and bills and they add up. And I suspect that in a lot of organizations,

00:09:45.799 --> 00:09:51.479
they're bigger than $7,400 a month. So if you can catch garbage data when it happens,

00:09:51.479 --> 00:09:58.159
that can save a lot of costs. Opportunity costs, I think, are another really important one to call

00:09:58.159 --> 00:10:03.280
out that are probably a lot less easy to point to, because they're not tangible. They didn't

00:10:03.280 --> 00:10:09.520
happen. You can't say I missed this thing, right? But philosophically, garbage data necessarily

00:10:09.520 --> 00:10:14.599
doesn't have any value. So any time you spend looking into it is time you should have been

00:10:14.599 --> 00:10:21.080
spending doing something else. But we're practical. We're not here for philosophy. And so from a

00:10:21.080 --> 00:10:25.880
practical perspective, you see that there's a lot of interesting things that you could be working on

00:10:25.880 --> 00:10:30.320
as a data professional, instead of plumbing the depths of these garbage data and trying to validate

00:10:30.320 --> 00:10:34.799
that your stakeholders might be able to find something or might not be able to find something.

00:10:34.799 --> 00:10:40.840
And I think that leads to another level of cost, which are these people costs. I like to learn

00:10:40.840 --> 00:10:46.840
things. I like to help other people learn things and kind of answer their questions. And you can't

00:10:46.840 --> 00:10:51.479
do that with garbage data. And eventually, after having to work with garbage data over and over and

00:10:51.479 --> 00:10:56.080
over again, data professionals are probably going to go find something else to do or go look for

00:10:56.080 --> 00:11:02.080
data that may or may not be garbage. I guess as a spoiler, the grass isn't greener everywhere. If

00:11:02.080 --> 00:11:06.159
anyone's worried about their organizations being especially borked, it's dirty everywhere. But

00:11:06.159 --> 00:11:12.159
people will continue to look if the data that they're working with isn't allowing them to learn

00:11:12.159 --> 00:11:18.119
things. And I think that that leads to maybe the most obvious kinds of costs, which are decision

00:11:18.119 --> 00:11:24.359
costs, right? Because if you're making decisions with garbage data, you don't know what's gonna

00:11:24.400 --> 00:11:30.880
happen, right? You're making decisions basically with random noise in a lot of cases. And that

00:11:30.880 --> 00:11:37.520
means something good could happen, but not because of any smart things we did. But lots of bad things

00:11:37.520 --> 00:11:43.200
could happen too. And that's why I think that ultimately these avoidable costs can really be

00:11:43.200 --> 00:11:49.200
catastrophic, right? So if you think about making bad decisions after all of your data professionals

00:11:49.200 --> 00:11:53.599
have left looking for greener pastures, after having spent all of your money retaining a bunch

00:11:53.640 --> 00:12:00.280
of garbage data, that feels like a recipe for disaster for an organization. And so the costs

00:12:00.280 --> 00:12:04.599
can really, really, really add up. Garbage data is something that we need to care a great deal

00:12:04.599 --> 00:12:11.400
about. So now I'm remembering my summary slides. So in summation part two, think about garbage data

00:12:11.400 --> 00:12:15.479
costs in a couple of different ways. Unavoidable costs, you're gonna have those anytime you have a

00:12:15.479 --> 00:12:22.760
data project. Avoidable costs though can be catastrophic. So finally, we should take action

00:12:22.799 --> 00:12:27.119
when we see garbage data. What does that mean though? So we're the primary deciders of data

00:12:27.119 --> 00:12:32.640
usefulness. The first thing I think it means is when people come to us with questions and bring

00:12:32.640 --> 00:12:38.679
us some data, we have to be honest with them and direct with them. I know that I don't like to give

00:12:38.679 --> 00:12:44.159
people bad news. At various points in my life, people have called me Jim the dream crusher. And

00:12:44.159 --> 00:12:50.719
I felt bad. It was a joke, but I felt bad about it. And I don't want to be in that position, but the

00:12:50.719 --> 00:12:55.080
consequences of not being honest and direct with your stakeholders and letting them know when

00:12:55.080 --> 00:12:59.320
garbage data happens are a lot worse than the consequences of having some bummed stakeholders.

00:12:59.320 --> 00:13:04.400
Now we don't want to bum any stakeholders out, but again, I think that we are obligated as the

00:13:04.400 --> 00:13:10.080
people who are kind of the line of defense against garbage data to say, this is garbage. Am I in five?

00:13:10.080 --> 00:13:16.760
Okay, cool. So the second thing, we don't want to bum people out. I think we need to lead with

00:13:16.760 --> 00:13:21.840
empathy. And this probably is just kind of par for the course for most of us, but it's useful to

00:13:21.840 --> 00:13:28.159
say it explicitly. Our stakeholders have a lot of things that they need. Our stakeholders have

00:13:28.159 --> 00:13:33.200
demands on them. They have pressures on them. They're not using garbage data or asking us to

00:13:33.200 --> 00:13:36.679
play around with garbage data because they think that it's a good way for us to spend their time.

00:13:36.679 --> 00:13:40.679
They're asking us because they need our help for something. And so if we're not leading with

00:13:40.679 --> 00:13:45.239
empathy, we end up with salty stakeholders who don't want to work with us anymore. And working

00:13:45.239 --> 00:13:50.479
with salty stakeholders is a good way to not have a job anymore or be a professional data

00:13:50.479 --> 00:13:58.159
professional anymore. Another useful thing to try and do is, if you can, influence your organization

00:13:58.159 --> 00:14:02.880
to treat all problems as data problems from the very beginning. All projects should be data

00:14:02.880 --> 00:14:08.520
projects until otherwise kind of considered. So default to treating projects as data projects.

00:14:08.520 --> 00:14:13.760
So an ideal workflow is when my stakeholders come to me with questions rather than coming

00:14:13.840 --> 00:14:18.919
to me with data, that gives me the opportunity and my team the opportunity to evaluate which

00:14:18.919 --> 00:14:23.440
data sets might be most appropriate to help them answer those questions, which makes it at least

00:14:23.440 --> 00:14:29.799
more likely that we're going to find something in there. And again, they may not be as happy as if

00:14:29.799 --> 00:14:33.400
you'd given them a huge pile of needles, but they'll be grateful that you didn't leave them

00:14:33.400 --> 00:14:39.760
empty-handed. And then finally, I think we have to be patient because organizations are used to

00:14:39.760 --> 00:14:45.359
doing things however they've been doing them. And coming in and saying, hey, you're doing it wrong,

00:14:45.359 --> 00:14:53.520
is never going to drive change. I have made that mistake. It's a bad idea. So be patient. Build

00:14:53.520 --> 00:15:00.080
those relationships. And if you do all of this stuff, like if you're, I think the third part

00:15:00.080 --> 00:15:03.239
here, the actions that we can take here is like, we have to be honest, we have to be empathetic,

00:15:03.239 --> 00:15:07.559
make sure we're treating all projects as data projects, and making sure that we're patient.

00:15:07.799 --> 00:15:11.400
I think that'll help us accomplish all three of these points here of being able to identify

00:15:11.400 --> 00:15:18.359
garbage data, the costs, making sure that we're taking action. And I guess to wrap it up, I mean,

00:15:18.359 --> 00:15:24.039
